{{Japanese name|Watsuji}} {{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Japanese philosophy]] |era = [[20th-century philosophy]] |image = Tetsuro Watsuji.jpg |name = Tetsuro Watsuji |birth_date = March 1, 1889 |birth_place = [[Himeji]], [[Hyōgo Prefecture]] |death_date = December 26, 1960 |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Kyoto School]] |main_interests = [[Aesthetics]], [[Ethics]], [[Culture]], [[Religion]] |influences = [[Kierkegaard]], [[Nietzsche]], [[Heidegger]], [[Kyoto School]], [[Natsume Sōseki]] |influenced = [[Yuasa Yasuo]] |notable_ideas = Climate and Culture, Rinrigaku Ethics }}
{{nihongo|Tetsuro Watsuji|和辻 哲郎|Watsuji Tetsurō|lead=yes}} (March 1, 1889 – December 26, 1960) was a [[Japan]]ese [[Ethics|moral philosopher]], [[Cultural history|cultural historian]], and [[Intellectual history|intellectual historian]].
==Early life== Watsuji was born in [[Himeji, Hyōgo|Himeji]], [[Hyōgo Prefecture]] to a physician. During his youth he enjoyed poetry and had a passion for [[Western literature]]. For a short time he was the coeditor of a literary magazine and was involved in writing poems and plays. His interests in philosophy came to light while he was a student at First Higher School in Tokyo, although his interest in literature would always remain strong throughout his life.
In his early writings (between 1913 and 1915) he introduced the work of [[Søren Kierkegaard]] to Japan, as well as working on [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], but in 1918 he turned against this earlier position, criticizing Western philosophical [[individualism]], and attacking its influence on Japanese thought and life. This led to a study of the roots of Japanese culture, including Japanese [[Buddhist art]], and notably the work of the medieval [[Zen Buddhism|Zen Buddhist]] [[Dōgen]]. Watsuji was also interested in the famous Japanese writer [[Natsume Sōseki]], whose books were influential during Watsuji's early years.
==Career== In the early 1920s Watsuji taught at [[Toyo University|Toyo]], [[Hosei University|Hosei]] and [[Keio University|Keio]] universities, and at [[Tsuda College|Tsuda Eigaku-juku]].<ref>David A. Dilworth, et al., ''Sourcebook for Modern Japanese Philosophy: Selected Documents'' (Westport, Conn.: Greenwood Press); cited in Robert Carter, "[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/watsuji-tetsuro/ Watsuji Tetsurô]", ''Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy'', 2004.</ref>
The issues of [[hermeneutics]] attracted his attention.<ref>Marra, Michael F. (2002). {{google books|VCcLEBldTagC|''Japanese hermeneutics,'' pp. 76-88.|page=76}}</ref>
In 1925 Watsuji became professor of ethics at [[Kyoto University]], joining the other leading philosophers of the time, [[Nishida Kitaro]] and [[Tanabe Hajime]]. He then moved to the Tokyo Imperial University in 1934 and held the chair in ethics until 1949.
During [[World War II]] his theories (which claimed the superiority of Japanese approaches to and understanding of human nature and ethics, and argued for the negation of self) provided support for [[Japanese nationalism]], a fact which, after the war, he said that he regretted.
Watsuji died at the age of seventy-one.
==Work== Watsuji's three main works were his two-volume 1954 ''History of Japanese Ethical Thought'', his three-volume ''Rinrigaku'' (''[[Ethics (Watsuji)|Ethics]]''), first published in 1937, 1942, and 1949, and his 1935 ''Fūdo''. The last of these develops his most distinctive thought. In it, Watsuji argues for an essential relationship between [[climate]] and other environmental factors and the nature of human [[culture]]s, and he distinguished three types of culture: pastoral, desert, and monsoon.<ref>The [[France|French]] philosopher [[Montesquieu]] had developed a theory along similar lines, though with very different conclusions.</ref>
==Writings== *1961–1963: ''Watsuji Tetsurō Zenshū'' (''Complete Works of Tetsuro Watsuji'') 20 volumes (Tokyo: Iwanami Shoten)
===English translations=== * 1961: ''Climate and Culture: A Philosophical Study'' trans. from {{nihongo4|''Fūdo''|風土}} by Geoffrey Bownas (Westport, CT: Greenwood Press) * 1969: ''Japanese Ethical Thought in the [[Noh]] Plays of the [[Muromachi Period]]'' trans. from chapter 4 of {{nihongo4|''Nihon Rinri Shisōshi''|日本倫理思想史}} by David A. Dilworth (''Monumenta Nipponica'' 24:4, 467-498) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2383883] * 1971: ''The Significance of Ethics As the Study of Man'' trans. from the introduction to {{nihongo4|''Rinrigaku''|倫理学}} vol. 1 by David A. Dilworth (''Monumenta Nipponica'' 26:3/4, 395-413) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2383653] * 1996: ''Watsuji Tetsurō's Rinrigaku: Ethics in Japan'' trans. from the first half of {{nihongo4|''Rinrigaku''|倫理学}} vol. 1 by Seisaku Yamamoto & Robert Carter (Albany: State University of New York Press) * 1998: Various essays in ''Sourcebook for Modern Japanese Philosophy'' by David Dilworth and Valdo Viglielmo with Agustin Jacinto Zavala. * 2009: ''Mask and Persona'' trans. from {{nihongo4|''Men to Perusona''|面とペルソナ}} by Carl M. Johnson [http://carlsensei.com/docs/translations/mask-and-persona.html] * 2009: ''The Psychology of [[Idol Worship]]'' trans. from {{nihongo4|''Gūzō Sūhai no Shinri''|偶像崇拝の心理}} by Carl M. Johnson [http://carlsensei.com/docs/translations/psychology-of-idol-worship.html] * 2011: ''Purifying Zen: Watsuji Tetsurō's Shamon Dōgen'' trans. from {{nihongo4|''Shamon Dōgen''|沙門道元}} by Steve Bein (Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press) [http://www.uhpress.hawaii.edu/shopcore/978-0-8248-3556-9/]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} * 2011: ''Pilgrimages to the Ancient Temples in [[Nara, Nara|Nara]]'' trans. from {{nihongo4|''Koji Junrei''|古寺巡礼}} by Hiroshi Nara (Portland, ME: MerwinAsia) (2012)[http://www.merwinasia.com/downloads/MACatalog_2012.pdf]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}
